e management e mail routing systems other computers are talking to us in spoken dialog systems for ordering betting trading and finding our missing luggage but what do they actually understand the bedrock of web search and speech call routing systems is keyword matching where the computer just matches exact words or perhaps variations so that network and networks match regardless of sentence structure this works a lot better than many people originally thought it would the frequency of words in a document gives the gist of its topic but this only gives a crude approximation of meaning one cannot distinguish emma sent an e mail to haresh from haresh sent an e mail to emma for tasks like understanding and responding to customer support e mail automatically one needs more language understanding one way to make this possible is to work with only a limited subset of language used in literal ways in a well understood context this is the basis of many speech dialog systems for activities like pizza ordering it is also the basis of a famous canadian machine translation system meteo which translates weather forecasts it is reasonable to say that meteo understands weather forecasts but much of language is written or spoken casually words and phrases often have many meanings to make up for example can mean to invent to resolve your differences and hug or to catch up on missed work people often don t specify what they mean for example i might say to a coworker i didn t get to work on the proposal i just expect her to know what proposal i mean these ambiguities have led to a surge in the use of probabilistic methods for language understanding because they provide principled and successful ways of dealing with uncertainties in meaning and interpretation for everyday human language there are still no systems that can understand words and their nuances half as well as humans but researchers are trying to change that for instance research systems we ve developed at stanford can interpret a sentence such as apple now sells the first imac computers that are powered by intel chips and correctly conclude some imac computers use intel cpus the aim is to shrink the gap between computer and human language understanding so that tasks like search based on meaning and e mail response generation become possible and successful last modified thu 12 jan 2012 at 9 24 stay connected itunes icon google+ icon facebook icon twitter icon linkedin icon stanford university school of engineering 475 via ortega stanford california 94305 4121 650.725 1575 1997 2012 stanford university all rights reserved accreditation info terms of use copyright complaints contact us
